image.asymptote:
// 3-D interactive (WebGL) figure.
import three; size(9cm); currentprojection=orthographic(5,2.6,3.2);
int nx=3,ny=2,nz=1; pen edge=gray(0.4)+linewidth(0.4pt);
for(int i=0;i<=nx;++i) for(int j=0;j<=ny;++j) draw((i,j,0)--(i,j,nz), edge);
for(int i=0;i<=nx;++i) for(int k=0;k<=nz;++k) draw((i,0,k)--(i,ny,k), edge);
for(int j=0;j<=ny;++j) for(int k=0;k<=nz;++k) draw((0,j,k)--(nx,j,k), edge);
draw(shift((2,1,0))*unitcube, red+opacity(0.45));
draw((2,1,0)--(3,1,0)--(3,2,0)--(2,2,0)--cycle, red+linewidth(0.6pt));
label("$\Delta V_{ijk}$", (2.5,1.5,1), 2N);
draw(O--(nx+1,0,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,ny+1,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O--(0,0,nz+1.3),gray,Arrow3);
label("$x$",(nx+1,0,0),S); label("$y$",(0,ny+1,0),E); label("$z$",(0,0,nz+1.3),N);

subsection.p:
For our room, E=[0,4]\times[0,3]\times[0,2]. The mass is
M \amp= \int_0^4\int_0^3\int_0^2 \left(1+\frac z2\right)\,dz\,dy\,dx \amp= \int_0^4\int_0^3 \left[z+\frac{z^2}{4}\right]_{0}^{2}\,dy\,dx \amp= \int_0^4\int_0^3 3\,dy\,dx \amp= \int_0^4 9\,dx \amp= 36.
So the gas has total mass \boxed{36\text{ kg}.}

There are six possible orders:

  \begin{array}{ccc}
  dz\,dy\,dx, \amp dz\,dx\,dy, \amp dy\,dz\,dx,\\
  dy\,dx\,dz, \amp dx\,dz\,dy, \amp dx\,dy\,dz.
  \end{array}

For boxes and well-behaved functions, all six orders give the same total.

statement.p:
Let
B=[a,b]\times[c,d]\times[e,f],
and suppose f is continuous on B. Then
\boxed{\iiint_B f(x,y,z)\,dV}
can be computed by any of the six iterated integrals. For example,
\boxed{\begin{aligned}
\iiint_B f\,dV
\amp= \int_a^b\int_c^d\int_e^f f(x,y,z)\,dz\,dy\,dx\\
\amp= \int_e^f\int_c^d\int_a^b f(x,y,z)\,dx\,dy\,dz.
\end{aligned}}
